If you simply linearize the system, what type of fixed point does the linearizat
ion predict?
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\dot{x} & = & -y+ax^{3}\\
\dot{y} & = & x+ay^{3}\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Find fixed points:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
ax^{3} & = & y\\
x & = & -ay^{3}\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\left(x^{*},y^{*}\right)=\left(0,0\right)\]

\end_inset

Linearize about the fixed point:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
J & = & \begin{bmatrix}3ax^{2} & -1\\
1 & 3ay^{2}\end{bmatrix}_{\left(0,0\right)}\\
 & = & \begin{bmatrix}0 & -1\\
1 & 0\end{bmatrix}\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Find eigenvalues:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
0 & = & \det\left\{ \lambda I-A\right\} =\begin{vmatrix}\lambda & -1\\
1 & \lambda\end{vmatrix}\\
0 & = & \lambda^{2}+1\\
\lambda & = & \pm i\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\therefore$
\end_inset

 we have a non-hyperbolic fixed point at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0\right)$
\end_inset

.
